Final Project¶

Systems & Technologies: Python

The Question / Problem¶

You have been hired as an indepedent auditor by Colorados Boulder County Assessors Office to help with the following problems.

Problem 1: Annual Report Insights (50 pts)¶

The Accessors Office is set to release their annual report on the valuation of residential single family properties. They have asked you to explore the data and produce at least 2 key findings they can share in their annual report to the public.

Problem 2: Estimate Home Values (45 pts)¶

The Assessors Office needs help improving their valuation process for residential single family properties. They have asked you to write a KNN alogorithm to value new homes based on similar home sales. By law, residential properties must be valued by using a "market approach". This predicts the price a property would bring on the open market in a transaction between a willing, informed, and knowledgeable buyer and seller. A property can be valued through the process of analyzing comparable sales. A comparable sale is any qualified sale in the last 5 years (January 2015 - December 2020).

The central factors used by the Assessors for property valuation are:

  • Location
  • Living Area (SQFT)
  • Age of the Home
  • Finished Basement

Problem 3: Ethics Review (5 pts)¶

Fairness and accuracy are vitally important. If the assessed values are too high, the property owners will overpay in taxes. If the assessed values are too low then we may fall short of the capital needed to cover the budget approved by legislators. As such, thinking through the impact of how we predict home prices is vitial.

Problem 1: EDA for the Annual Report Insights¶

Goal¶

Perform EDA on the property valuations for "1-Story" and "2-3 Story" single family residential buildings. Identify at least 2 key insights and/or graphs that tell a story about the valuations for these properties for the annual report.

1.0 Get the Data (15 pts)¶

Tasks:

  1. Read in the following data:
    • buildings.csv
    • land.csv
    • values.csv
    • owner_addresses.csv
  2. Adjust the structure of our data as necessary (joins, drop unneeded columns, add features, etc).
  3. Inspect and handle missing values as necessary.

Note: These files have been pre-filtered to only include single family properties. Additionaly, in some tables columns have been dropped before sending you the data (such as owner name in owner_addresses). Complete meta data about each file can be found in the "ar-property-data-download-help.pdf" document.

Note :- I have seperated sections (1.0,1.1 etc) in each Problem and tasks in each section with blue lines and I have divided each Problem (1,2,3) with black lines for clarity. Also, I have seperated each plot of Univariate data and Bivariate data with brown lines.¶

# Converting the land value in acres to square feet so that all the rows are uniform in terms of land unit type.
# 1 acre = 43560 Square Feet

for idx,row in land_df.iterrows():
    if row['landUnitType'] == 'AC':
        land_df.at[idx,'landUnitValue'] = row['landUnitValue']*43560
        land_df.at[idx,'landUnitType'] = 'SF'

Part II: Algorithmic Thinking¶

Objective¶

In this portion of the assignment, our goal is to predict the value of a new single-family property given comparable sales data. One way we might estimate the value of a home is to look at the value of k-similar nearby homes that have recently sold. The average sales price of those k homes could then be used as the predicted valuation for our new home. This process is effectively how the K-Nearest Neighbor Algorithm (KNN) works for regression problems.

KNN is considered a supervised machine learning algorithm that can be used to solve both classification and regression problems. As shown above, we can be used to solve nonparametric regression problems such as predicting the price of a new home based on similar nearby homes.

Recall the central factors used for property valuation:

  • Location
  • Living Area (SQFT)
  • Age of the Home
  • Finished Basement

2.1 Property Valuation using KNN (20 pts)¶

Tasks:

  • Complete the below function predict_knn() so that it finds the k-most similar sales properties in the appraisal neighborhood (nh) and returns the average sale price for those k properties as the predicted value (y_hat).

How this problem will be graded:

  • You will not be graded on your prediction accuracy or the value of k you select. You will be graded on how you write your code and, in particular, if you took advantage of vectorization. You must write your own knn function from scratch, do not use sklearn.neighbors.KNeighborsRegressor.

KNN Regression Pseudo Code¶

Given a new data point:

  1. Calculate the Euclidean distance between the new data point and all known datapoints in the dataset.
  2. Select the k closest datapoints.
  3. Average the target variable for the k closest data points.

Euclidean Distance formula for 3-dimenstions where p_1 and q_1 is finished_sqft, p2 and q_2 is home_age, and p3 and q_3 is finished_basement:

$$d(p,q)=\sqrt{(p_1-q_1)^2 + (p_2-q_2)^2 + (p_3-q_3)^2}$$

.

KNN Regression Algorithm - Solution¶

In [72]:
import math 

def predict_knn(sales_data, k=3, nh=200, finished_sqft=1500, home_age=5, finished_basement=False):
    sales_data[1:5]
    # Filter down to our sales data to the provided neighborhood number, nh.
    sales_data = sales_data[sales_data.nh == nh]
    
    point_distances = []
    eu_dist = 0
    # Calculate the Euclidean Distance for finished_sqft, home_age, and finished_basement for every sale in our nh.
    for index, row in sales_data.iterrows():
        eu_dist = math.sqrt(abs(((row['total_finished_sqft'] - finished_sqft)^2) +
                        ((row['home_age'] - home_age)^2) +
                        ((row['bsmt_flag'] - finished_basement)^2)))
        point_distances.append(eu_dist)
    
    sales_data['eu_dist'] = point_distances

    sales_data_least_3 = sales_data.nsmallest(k,'eu_dist')
    # Keep only the *k* closeset rows and take the mean of our target variable "price"
    y_hat = round(pd.Series(sales_data_least_3['price']).mean(),2)
    
    return y_hat

Explanation of the KNN Regression Algorithm Code = I get the sales_data and I filter the data based on the neighbourhood.I then create point_distances as a list object. I iterate the sales_data in a for loop and caluclate the Euclidean Distance using the formula. I then append the caluclated Euclidean Distance to a new column called 'eu_dist' based on each row.I use the nsmallest() function on the new column based on the k-value to get the k-number of smallest 'eu_dist' and then once I got those rows, I take the price column values of those rows and take the mean of those values. I round it up to 2 decimals and return the value as y_hat. This y_hat value is the predicted value(price) for that particular k,nh,finished_sqft home_age and finished_basement that I pass in the function call.

import math

sample_size = 50
data_50 = all_data_with_sales.sample(n=sample_size)

knn_results = {}
knn_results_difference = {}
k_value = 1
optimal_k_value = None
count = 0
for idx,row in data_50.iterrows():
    predictor_value = predict_knn(all_data_with_sales, k=k_value, nh=row['nh'], finished_sqft=row['total_finished_sqft'], 
                            home_age=row['home_age'], finished_basement=row['bsmt_flag'])
    tuple_value = (predictor_value,row['total_actual_val'])
    knn_results[k_value] = (tuple_value)
    if count == 0:
        min_difference = round(abs(predictor_value - row['total_actual_val']),2)
        count += 1
    difference = round(abs(predictor_value - row['total_actual_val']),2)
    if min_difference >= difference:
        min_difference = difference
        optimal_k_value = k_value
    knn_results_difference[k_value] = difference
    k_value += 1

Explanation of the code to test the KNN Function we created = I take a sample of 50 rows from the data frame all_data_with_sales and call it data_50. I create two dictionaries knn_results and knn_results_difference. knn_results stores k-value as the key and tuple of the predicted-value and the actual-value(total_actual_val). knn_results_difference stores k-value and the difference of predicted-value and the actual-value(total_actual_val). I iterate the rows of data_50 and I call the predict_knn for each iteration and get the predictor_value. I store the values in knn_results and knn_results_difference based on above. The k-value is incremented for each iteration and predict_knn() function is called for k values from 1 to 50.

Explanation to Question - 2.2 Test your KNN function - How do your predictions perform relative to the Accessor's valuation as you try different values of k.¶

Answer = I have taken the difference between the predictor value and the accessor value in order to find optimal k value as that would give me the k-value where the predictor value is closest to the true value (Accessor Value). 2. What potential harm could arise due to how our knn regression algorithm works?¶

(a). For example, what if k is too low or too high?¶
(b). What impact can outliers have? Would it make sense to normalize (e.g. standardize our values between 0 and 1) for our data points (sqft, age, basement) before calculating Euclidean Distance?¶

Answer = If the value of 'k' is small then it causes Low Bias, High variance - overfitting of the model. If 'k' is very large then it leads to High Bias, Low variance - underfitting of the model. The optimal K value can be modeled in different ways but I have selected the way where the optimal k-value is the minimum difference between the predicted value of the house (price) and the accessor value of the house (total_actual_val).

Outliers can impact the Euclidean Distance values and that could impact the mean of the prices so it would make sense to normalize (e.g. standardize our values between 0 and 1) for our data points (sqft, age, basement) before calculating Euclidean Distance.

3. Should we have an appeal process for people that may be harmed by the results of our model = Yes, the model¶

Answer = If the KNN algorithm is not perfect, it could impact the predicted value of the house and that could impact the sale of the house.
